Title: Balancing Security, Performance, Reliability, Scalability and Cost
Detail: The technical platform for ZBPro shall be selected and designed to optimize for a balance of security, performance, reliability, scalability, and cost
column5:
Technical Platform Constraint
Implementation
The technical platform for ZBPro shall be selected and designed to optimize for a balance of security, performance, reliability, scalability, and cost. The platform shall leverage the best of the breed, standards-based technologies.
 		The system uses the Amazon AWS cloud platform. In particular, the system
  • uses the ALB to scale horizontally when incoming traffic increases or decreases by adding or deleting EC2 instances.
  • uses the EFS to scale file systems automatically as files are added, removed and burse to higher throughput levels when necessary.
  • uses the EFS to securely and reliably access data files with a managed file system in Amazon AWS for 99.999999999% durability and up to 99.99% of availability(https://aws.amazon.com/efs/).
  • uses the RDS, fully managed at AWS for MariaDB services, without needing to provision infrastructure or maintain software, achieve high availability with RDS multi-AZ deployments, and benefit from proven security best practices in databases born in the cloud(https://aws.amazon.com/rds).
  • uses the EB that automatically handles the deployment, from capacity provisioning, load balancing, auto-scaling to application health monitoring. Meanwhile through its dashboard, ZBPro has full control over the AWS resources powering the ZBPro-API. There is no additional charge for the EB and only the AWS resources needed to store and run the ZBPro-API are charged(https://aws.amazon.com/elasticbeanstalk/).
  • uses the IAM in AWS to grant role-based security credentials to authorize personals that access the ZBPro resources, and specify who can access services and resources in AWS, centrally manage fine-grained role-based permissions to AWS resources, prevention of unauthorized users.

Title: Minimize Attack Surface area and Blast Radius
Detail: Minimize attack surface area and blast radius of a potential attack
column5:
Security Constraint
 		Implementation
Minimize attack surface area and blast radius of a potential attack.
  		The business processing functionality leverages interfaces that are only available on a private network (AWS VPC (virtual private network)). These interfaces are not available to the general public or even customers and customer networks. Access to the virtual private network is limited to only the presentation layer (web front end) of the ZBPro application.

The ZBPro web application (presentation layer) is the only service that exposes an endpoint outside of a private network. This endpoint is hosted on an AWS elastic load balancer. Access to the public endpoint is limited to customer managed IP ranges. For example, a customer may employ 300 users that require access to ZBPro. The load balancer is configured to block all traffic, except that originating from the customer network via customer managed outbound IP addresses, typically a small range of IP addresses.

Access to the public load balanced IP address is also limited to a single port. The limited set of users that can access the load balancer can only do so on port 443 via an SSL encrypted protocol.

Title: ZBPro Independent of Wi-Fi
Detail: The use of Wi-Fi shall be independent of the ZBPro product
column5:
Security Constraint
 		Implementation
The use of Wi-Fi shall be independent of the ZBPro product
 		The use of Wi-Fi is independent of the ZBPro product and is out of the product scope as it pertains to the functionality and security posture of the ZBPro product.

The ZBPro software will not connect to any wireless networks. There will be no capability built into the product for this functionality. ZBPro is hosted within runtime environments provided by AWS services. These services provide a capability to connect to a physical, wired network.

The ZBPro software is not a portable device that would be able to connect to a wireless network. It is hosted within AWS and is only connected to AWS VPC’s (private networks) managed by ZBeats administrators.

ZBPro web application has a public IP address hosted on an AWS Application Load Balancer. Access to this endpoint is limited to restricted customer networks.

Risk for this type of connection is covered in 08122022 Cybersecurity Threat Assessment Report by Harbor Labs.

Title: ZBPro Remote Access Restrictions
Detail: Remote access to ZBPro software shall be restricted
column5:
Security Constraint
 		Implementation
Remote access to ZBPro software shall be restricted.
 		The ZBPro software is hosted in AWS accounts managed by ZBeats. It is remotely accessible by only a limited administrative team. This team has the required access to update and maintain the software.  All administrative access and control is centrally managed in the hosting environments in AWS.

Customers can access the web interface for the application, but only have access to execute specific actions based on their roles. There are no settings that affect the core functionality of the product that can be changed remotely through the product interface.

Title: Securing Data in Transit System
Detail: Data in the transit system shall be secured
column5:
Security Constraint
Implementation
Data in the transit system shall be secured
 		First, the data in the transit from the ZBPro-UI (a user’s web browser) and ZBPro-API (the backend server) is secured by the HTTPS with a valid SSL certificate. Second, the EFS system of the ZBPro-API file systems always encrypt the data at rest and in transit by enabling the TLS.

Title: Principle of Least Privilege
Detail: ZBPro shall ensure the principle of least privilege which means enforcing a minimum level of user rights that allow the user to perform the user's role
column5:
Security Constraint
Implementation
ZBPro shall ensure the principle of least privilege which means enforcing a minimum level of user rights that allow the user to perform the user's role
Each user is required to login with their credentials. The user's credentials are tied to their user role. Only tasks and features the user is expected to perform based on their role will be visible and accessible to the user. For API calls, the user will submit the API call with their token/credentials. The token/credentials will be checked to determine if they meet the privilege requirement for the API. If the token/credentials do not meet the privilege, then the API call is denied.

Title: Authenticating the Users
Detail: ZBPro shall authenticate the users to ensure the system and data is accessed authorized users
column5:
Security Constraint
Implementation
ZBPro shall authenticate the users to ensure the system and data is accessed authorized users.
 		First, each user must use password and MFA to access the ZBPro frontend web browsers. Also, a user role is placed to control the access of different user roles (such as HCP, technician, medical supervisor and admins). Second the ZBPro management users use the IAM management to control over access to AWS resources where ZBPro deploys. Both a strong password policy and an MFA (multi-factor access) are enforced. Data is only accessed to authorized users with required user roles.

Title: Protect the exposure of Patient Data
Detail: ZBPro shall protect the exposure of patients' data and ensure the security and integrity of user-uploaded files
column5:
Security Constraint
Implementation
ZBPro shall protect the exposure of patients' data and ensure the security and integrity of user-uploaded files. 
 		The ZBPro uses the RDS and EFS services to persist the user data and data files including user-uploaded files. Each user-uploaded file passes integrity checks. RDS provides security to stored user data: it disables public access, encrypted at all times, available at multiple available zones, storage autoscaling, enabled deletion protection, running logs, automatic backups and central monitoring. EFS provides security to stored data files: it enables multiple availability zones, encryption for at-rest and in-transit, automatic backups and auto-scaling, and central monitoring.

Title: Protecting AWS Access
Detail: The access to AWS where ZBPro is deployed shall be protected
column5:
Security Constraint
Implementation
The access to AWS where ZBPro is deployed shall be protected.
 		ZBPro uses the IAM management to have full control over the AWS access: only authorized users can access to the AWS resources where ZBPro is deployed. Both a strong password policy (minimal length is 8, require at least one uppercase letter, one lowercase letter, one number and one non-alphanumeric character) and MFA (multi-factor access) are enforced. Meanwhile a role-based access policy is used to provide minimal authorization to management users to the ZBPro resources.

Title: S3 Credential Storage Restrictions
Detail: S3 credentials shall not be stored in the config files as plain text
column5:
Security Constraint
Implementation
S3 credentials shall not be stored in the config files as plain text
 		ZBPro did not use S3 credentials and uses password protections for all credentials including the RDS credentials.

Title: Persist the Data and User Files
Detail: The system shall be able to persist the data and user files securely and reliably
column5:
Persistence Constraint
Implementation
The system shall be able to persist the data and user files securely and reliably
 		The system uses the RDS and EFS to persist the data and user files. (1) RDS persists the user data (including name, address, etc.) and it disables public access, encrypted at all times, available at multiple available zones, storage autoscaling, enabled deletion protection, running logs, automatic backups and central monitoring. (2) EFS persists the data files (including the ECG data, annotations, etc.) and it enables multiple availability zones, encryption for at-rest and in-transit, automatic backups and auto-scaling, and central monitoring.

Title: Computing Power Management
Detail: The system shall have the capability to increase or decrease computing power when required and shall be available 95% of the time
column5:
Reliability/Availability (Failover) Constraint
Implementation
The system shall have the capability to increase or decrease computing power when required and shall be available 95% of the time. 
 		The ZBPro uses the EB environment that has automatically handled the auto-scaling of computing power (EC2 instances) when application workload changes. Meanwhile, we uses multiple availability zones (multi-AZ) settings to increases the availability.

Title: System Scaling
Detail: The system shall be able to scale based on incoming traffic
column5:
Performance Constraint Implementation
The system shall be able to scale based on incoming traffic. To ensure consistent performance, the system shall scale horizontally when incoming traffic increases or decreases. The software must be designed to function in scenarios where each functional component can scale vertically (increase compute power to a single node) and/or horizontally (prevision additional nodes to distribute workload) by adding new instances of AWS EC2 or EBS or increasing resource allocation to existing instances. 

In particular, the ZBPro uses the Application Load Balancer (ALB) to automatically distributes incoming traffic across multiple instances in multiple available zones. This balances the workloads. It also automatically increases or decreases the number of instances as the demand of incoming traffics increases or decreases. This ensures the performance of the software. It also monitors the health of instances: if an instance fails, it will add new instances to replace the failure nodes.

Title: Hosting Enviorment Configuration
Detail: The hosting environment shall be configurable depending on the need
column5:
Performance Constraint
Implementation
The hosting environment shall be configurable depending on the need.
 		The ZBPro-API system uses the EB (Elastic Beanstalk) environment as the ZBPro-API and ZBPro-Algo hosting environment for deploying and scaling API applications and services as needed. The EB automatically handles the deployment of backend services, by connecting the EFS and RDS systems, provisioning EC2 instances, load balancing (using ALB), auto-scaling (increasing and decreasing EC2 instances based on incoming traffics) and providing application health monitoring. Depending on the need, we have complete resource control including EC2 instance types and processor types that are optimal for our backends, and scales up/down using adjustable Auto Scaling settings.

Title: Preprocess Module
Detail: Preprocess Module, implemented in the DataProcessService class in Java, is designed to preprocess the data uploaded from the user interface
column5:
Preprocess Module, implemented in the DataProcessService class in Java, is designed to preprocess the data uploaded from the user interface. It also validates the data formats and checks the integrity of data, and then converts them into the ZBPro data formats.
Inputs:
This module requires the data uploaded from the user interface.
Outputs:
This module outputs the metadata, the app status of the record, and the ECG tracing files.
Structure and Methodology:
This module is designed to preprocess raw data that is uploaded from the user interface and converts them to the ZBPro data formats and also validate the data during this process. The figure below shows each step of this process as follows: (Step 1) raw data files input into the process; (Step 2) read the basic information of the recording including the bit resolution, sample rate, lead information, duration, etc., (Step 3) verify the basic information to ensure the requirements are satisfied. (Step 4) if it does not satisfy any of the requirements, it will not be a valid record then the data preprocess exits. (Step 5) if it satisfies all requirements, the record data will continue to be processed. (Step 6) the record data will be written into different data files including a metadata file (for sample rate, ADC gain, and zero), an app status file (for recording time and duration), and ECG tracing data files (one data file for each lead). (Step 7) upon completion of all data files, the data preprocessing succeeds. The data formats such as metadata, app status, and ECG tracings are defined in Section 1.4 .
Figure #: The structure of preprocess uploaded data

Title: QRS Detection Module
Detail: QRS Detection Module, implemented in the BeatDetectionAndClassification class, is designed to detect the QRS peaks
column5:
QRS Detection Module, implemented in the BeatDetectionAndClassification class, is designed to detect the QRS peaks.
Inputs:
This module requires the metadata, app status, and ECG tracing.
Outputs:
BeatDetectionAndClassification outputs the detected cardiac beats using the formats:
  • Beat samples: An array of 4-byte integers, each integer presenting the index of a cardiac beat in the entire recording.
  • Beat symbols: An array of 1-byte characters, each character presenting the label of a cardiac beat, where N is for sinus beat, V is for PVC and Q is for a questionable beat.
Structures and Methodology:
BeatDetectionAndClassification is implemented in Java as a class, and it incorporates a series of methods as follows:
  • Resampling: input raw ECG tracing and resampled to 250 Hz.
  • Bandpass filter: a digital bandpass filter with the pass-band 0.5-50Hz to reduce false detections caused by various types of interference present in ECG signals.
  • Wavelet filter: a wavelet filter is used to remove the baseline wandering of the tracing.
  • A rule-based method to detect QRS peaks:
    • Ignore all peaks that precede or follow larger peaks by less than 200 ms.
    • If a QRS peak occurs, check to see whether the raw signal contains both positive and negative slopes. If not, the peak represents a baseline shift.
    • If the peak occurred within 360 ms of a previous detection check to see if the maximum derivative in the raw signal was at least half the maximum derivative of the previous detection. If not, the peak is assumed to be a T-wave.
    • If the peak is larger than the detection threshold, call it a QRS, otherwise call it noise.
    • If no QRS has been detected within 1.5 R-to-R intervals, there was a peak that was larger than half the detection threshold, and the peak followed the preceding detection by at least 360 ms, classifying that peak as a QRS complex.
  • A Signal Quality Index (SQI) for artifact detection: within a time window, calculate qSQI, pSQI, cSQI, kSQI, basSQI for the tracing to detect the artifacts.
    • qSQI: assesses QRS peaks detection matching degree.
    • pSQI: assesses the power spectrum distribution feature.
    • cSQI: assesses the variability of R-R intervals.
    • kSQI: the fourth moment (kurtosis) of the ECG tracing distribution.
    • basSQI: assesses the relative power in the ECG tracing baseline.

Title: PVC classifier Module
Detail: PVC classifier, implemented in detect_pvc(), is designed to classify the ventricular ectopic beats
column5:
PVC classifier, implemented in detect_pvc(), is designed to classify the ventricular ectopic beats.
Inputs:
This module requires the metadata, the app status, and the ECG tracing and detected QRS peaks.
Outputs:
This module classifies the VEB beats and labels them as V in the beat symbols file.
Structure and Methodology:
This classifier is to detect the V beats from detected QRS peaks. As shown in Figure 6 , this structure is comprised of a rule-based V-beat detection method 2 , a rule-based reference pattern search and match method 5 , and a neural network-based binary predictor 9 that is accompanied by a rule-based validation method 10 .
Figure #: The structure of the PVC classifier

The components in Figure 6 are briefly described as follows.
Component
Methodology/Explanation
1
Input detected QRS peaks
2
A rule-based based classifier to classify the N and V beats
3
Rule-based detected V beats
4
Rule-based detected N beats
5
Rule-based reference pattern searching and matching: consecutive N beats are used to generate reference patterns according to the correlation between each pair of the beat tracing; other N beats are compared with the reference pattern, resulting in “confirmed N beats” and “suspect N beats”.
6
Confirmed N beats in 5 .
7
Suspect N beats in 5 .
8
Validate PVC_NN: if N beats reference templates are found, they are passed into the PVC_NN. If the prediction of template beats being N is above a threshold, the PVC_NN is validated and is used to further validate “suspect N beats”.
9
A binary neural network-based predictor to classify the PVC beats.
10
Verify the V beats classified by the PVC neural network by comparing its QRS height, width, and area with classified N beats.
11
Output V beats
12
Output N beats

Title: Ventricular events detection module
Detail: Ventricular events detection module, implemented in the detect_v_events(), is designed to detect the ventricular events including
column5:
Ventricular events detection module, implemented in the detect_v_events(), is designed to detect the ventricular events including:
  • Ventricular Bigeminy (VBi)
  • Ventricular Trigeminy (VTri)
  • Ventricular Couplets (Vc)
  • Ventricular Tachycardia (VT)
Inputs:
This module requires the metadata, the app status and the ECG tracing, and the detected beats and classification.
Outputs:
This module detects ventricular events and writes the detected events in the JSON format as defined in Figure 1 .
Structure and Methodology:
This module uses rule-based methods. The following table presents the methodology and explanation for the detection rules of ventricular arrhythmias:
Arrhythmias
Methodology/Explanation
VT
Occurrence of 3 or more ventricular ectopic beats (V) in a row with an average heart rate >= 100 bpm;
•    All the beats in the events shall be categorized as V.
•    If >30 seconds = sustained
•    Can be monomorphic or polymorphic
Ventricular Couplet
Exact two ventricular (V) beats in a row.
Ventricular Bigeminy
Single premature ventricular beat (V) following each sinus beat (N) in at least 3 consecutive cycles, i.e., NVNVNV.
•    Every other beat is a premature ventricular beat
Ventricular Trigeminy
Single premature ventricular beat (V) following every two sinus beats in at least 3 consecutive cycles, i.e., NNVNNVNNV.
•    Every third beat is a premature ventricular beat

Title: Atrial fibrillation/flutter events detection module
Detail: Atrial fibrillation/flutter events detection module, implemented in the detect_afib(), is designed to detect the atrial fibrillation and irregular flutter (AF) event
column5:
Atrial fibrillation/flutter events detection module, implemented in the detect_afib(), is designed to detect the atrial fibrillation and irregular flutter (AF) event.
Inputs:
This module requires the metadata, the app status and the ECG tracing, and the detected beats and classification.
Outputs:
This module detects AF events and writes the detected events in the JSON format as defined in Figure 1 .
Structure and Methodology:
This module uses mostly rule-based methods, among which a neural network-based binary classifier AF_NN is added for the re-validation of possible AF rhythms. As shown in Figure 7 , this module starts with a rule-based method to detect AF rhythm 4 . Next, a suspect AF rhythm in 4 shall be re-validated by AF_NN 7 . Further, an AF rhythm detected by AF_NN shall be re-validated by another three different verification methods 9 - 11 before it can be confirmed as AF rhythm.
Figure #: The structure of the AF classifier

The components in Figure 7 are briefly described as follows.
Component
Methodology/Explanation
1
Input QRS peaks
2
RR intervals calculated based on QRS peaks
3
Heart rate variability (HRV) is calculated based on RR intervals as AF features
4
Rule-based AF detection: use HRV and the mean, standard deviation, and ratios of the RR intervals within a time window to determine if the tracing in that window is AF, possible AF, or non-AF.
5
Detected AF by the rule-based AF detection method.
6
Suspect AF by the rule-based AF detection method.
7
AF_NN detection (NN using HRV): for suspect AF detected in 4 , calculate the HRV for the tracing and pass HRV features as the input to the AF_NN to re-classify whether that tracing is AF or non-AF.
8
Rule-based P-wave verification: for potential AF rhythm from AF_NN, re-verify the existence and similarities of the P wave, then output non-AF and possible AF.
9
Rule-based RR interval verification: for possible AF from 8 , use RR intervals to re-verify if the rhythm is regular or irregular, then output non-AF and possible AF.
10
Rule-based heart rate verification: for possible AF from 9 , use heart rate to re-verify if the rhythm could be AF rhythm, then output non-AF and verified AF.
11
AF rhythms that passed all detection and validation methods.

Title: The sinus rhythm detection module
Detail: The sinus rhythm detection module implements functions including
column5:
The sinus rhythm detection module implements functions including: detect_nsr(), detect_tachy(), detect_brady(), and detect_pause(). This module is designed to detect the following arrhythmias:
  • Normal Sinus Rhythm (NSR)
  • Sinus Tachycardia (Tachy)
  • Sinus Bradycardia (Brady)
  • Pause (Pause)
Inputs:
This module requires the metadata, the app status and the ECG tracing, and the detected beats and classification.
Outputs:
This module detects the events and writes the detected events in the JSON format as defined in Figure 1 .
Structure and Methodology:
This module is a rule-based method. The following table presents the methodology and explanation for the detection rules of these arrhythmias:
Component
Methodology/Explanation
detect_pause()
A single-time prolonged R-R interval either due to sinus arrest or AV Block from increased vagal tone; between two consecutive QRS is ≥2 seconds.
  • Typical increased vagal tone means PP interval markedly increases, accompanied by PR interval prolongation or/and non-conducted P wave.
  • Current RR interval >= 2 second;
  • Preceding and succeeding RR intervals are shorter than the current RR intervals by at least 10%.
detect_brady()
Sinus rhythm with a sinus rate < 60 bpm in adults. Sinus bradycardia needs to be longer than 5 QRSs.
  • Normal upright P wave in lead II preceding every QRS complex
  • QRS complex succeeding each P wave.
  • Sinus rate < 60 bpm
  • Ventricular rate < 60 bpm (typical 1:1)
detect_tachy()
Sinus rhythm with a sinus rate > 100 bpm in adults. Sinus Tachycardia needs to be longer than 5 QRSs.
  • Normal upright P wave in lead II preceding every QRS complex
  • QRS complex succeeding each P wave.
  • Sinus rate > 100 bpm
  • Ventricular rate > 100 bpm (typical 1:1)
detect_nsr()
Normal sinus rhythm refers to the electrical pulse originating from the sinus node that properly propagates throughout the heart at a rate between 60 and 100 beats per minute (bpm) in adults.
  • Normal upright P wave in lead II preceding every QRS complex
  • QRS complex succeeding each P wave.
  • Sinus rate is between 60 and 100 bpm
  • Ventricular rate is between 60 and 100 bpm (typical 1:1)
postprocess()
An episode that belongs to none of the detected events is marked as unclassified.

Title: Data Summarization Module
Detail: This module is designed to summarize the data to support the report
column5:
This module is designed to summarize the data to support the report. The report data includes the patient and record information, as well as a summary of detected beat and arrhythmias, and selected ECG strips to print in the report for display.
Input:
This module requires ECG tracing, and the detected beats and arrhythmias.
Output:
This module outputs a summary of detected beats and arrhythmias:
  • Patient basic information such as patient name, sex, and age.
  • Record basic information such as recording start and end times, and duration.
  • Heart rate summary and burden.
  • Patient symptoms.
  • Summary of ectopic beats such as VEB counts and burden.
  • Summary of arrhythmias such as event counters, AF duration & burden, etc.
  • Mandatory strips in the summary page of a report such as AF, Pause, and VT.
  • HRV results.
  • Index of selected ECG strips to print in the report.
  • Narrative findings from the technician and medical supervisor.

Title: Logging with SLF4J Logger
Detail: Logging with SLF4J Logger
column5:
Logging with SLF4J Logger:
The Simple Logging Facade for Java (SLF4J) is used as the logging framework. It allows the ZBPro system to log all API fails (errors and warnings) at the deployment time and log additional debug messages as development time. All the API error and warning logs will persist on the backend file systems and can be accessed by only authorized users.

Title: MyBatis Framework
Detail: MyBatis Framework
column5:
MyBatis Framework:
The MyBatis framework is used to provide database service. This eliminates almost all of the JDBC code and manual setting of parameters and retrieval of results. Also, it executes SQL safely and maps parameter objects to JDBC-prepared statement parameters. This lowers the risk of SQL injection.

Title: Spring MVC Custom Validation
Detail: Spring MVC Custom Validation
column5:
Spring MVC Custom Validation:
The Spring MVC framework provides the use of validation API. The validation API puts constraints on the user input using annotations and can validate both client-side and server-side. It provides standard predefined validators like @Min, @Max, @Size, @Pattern, and @NotNull. In case we have to process a more specific input spring MVC also provides the concept of user-defined validators with custom validation logic. Thus, this framework allows us to validate a length, number, regular expression, etc., and also can customize validators, e.g., filtering out special characters in input and limiting the size of the input, etc.

Title: Security Configurations
Detail: Security Configurations
column5:
Security Configurations:
The frontend UI needs to enable the following functions:

  • The ZBPro Web GUI does not cache any PHI/PII on the user's laptop/PC.
  • The ZBPro has input validation in all form fields both on the client side and server side.
  • The ZBPro Web GUI will check the version of a web browser. It shows an error if the web browser is not Google Chrome or its version is less than 100.

Title: Banner Management
Detail: Banner Management
column5:
Banner Management:
A system information banner is placed at the top of the login website and shows a message to all users. This message notifies users of a system level information including when the system will be unavailable due to maintenance and system update etc.

Title: Create a record
Detail: Create a record
column5:
Create a record:
When an HCP is creating a Record, the following process is followed.

Steps
Explanation/Illustration
Step 1
The HCP needs to select a patient from their organization's patient list or create a new patient if it is a new patient.
Step 2
Assign for an associate service group to analyze the data for the Record.
Step 3
Select the Monitor Type. When the selected Monitor Type type is Holter type, the HCP must enter the start time of ECG data.
Step 4
Select the “Duration”. The ZBPro provides five options: 24hours, 48hours, 7days, 14days, 30days.
Step 5
Enter the start time of ECG data.
Step 6
Submit this form and then the ZBPro will double-check that the fields filled in are correct.

Title: Upload data to a record
Detail: Upload data to a record
column5:
Upload data to a record:

Steps
Explanation/Illustration
Step 1
 Find the Record that needs to upload data from the Record list.                     
Step 2
 Click the data-uploading icon for that Record.
Step 3
 Drag and drop the local ECG data file into the upload box. The ZBPro will check the selected file's format and suffix to ensure it matches the file rules.
Step 4
 Click Next and enter the contents of the patient diary. If the data file has not been uploaded, you will not be able to click the Next button.
Step 5
 Click Upload. The patient's information will be confirmed again.
Step 6
 When the backend returns the results, the interface will show whether the upload interface is successful or not.
Uploading is in progress:


Upload is successfully done:

Title: Create a patient
Detail: Create a patient
column5:
Create a patient:
The ZBPro will always verify that the patient is wearing a pacemaker when creating the patient.

Title: ECG Visualization
Detail: ECG Visualization
column5:
ECG Visualization:
Display ECG tracing and events including detected arrhythmias and patient-triggered events.
The ZBPro supports three resolutions: 720p,1080p, 4k.

Title: Display Resolution
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall be supported in displays of 720p resolution.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall be supported in displays of 720p resolution.

Title: Sampling Rate
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG data with a minimum of 200Hz sampling rate
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG data with a minimum of 200Hz sampling rate.

Title: Bit Resolution
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG data between 11 and 16-bit resolution.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG data between 11 and 16-bit resolution.

Title: ECG Leads
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG data in Lead I, Lead II, Modified Lead I, and Modified Lead II for analysis
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG data in Lead I, Lead II, Modified Lead I, and Modified Lead II for analysis.

Title: Record Duration
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG records of 24 hours to 30 days duration.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall be compatible with ECG records of 24 hours to 30 days duration.

Title: Data Integrity Check
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall perform a data integrity check on ECG data.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall perform a data integrity check on ECG data.

Title: Sampling Rate and Bit Resolution Rejection
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall reject ECG data not compatible with bit resolution or sampling rate
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall reject ECG data not compatible with bit resolution or sampling rate.

Title: System and Software Compatibility
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall be accessible and maintain compatibility with a Windows PC running Windows 10
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall be accessible and maintain compatibility with a Windows PC running Windows 10.0.19044 Version 21H2 Build 19044 or later, or Windows 11 Version 21H2 Build 22000,  with Google Chrome:  Version 103.0.5060.114 or later and prevent access from web browsers other than Google Chrome.

Title: Diary entry display
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall display patient diary entry events where they occurred in a timeline
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall display patient diary entry events where they occurred in a timeline.

Title: ECG View and Annotation Tools
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall provide tools for ECG Technician to view and annotate ECG data with the following features
column5:
ZBPro(TM) shall provide tools for ECG Technician to view and annotate ECG data with the following features:
  • Condensed View to observe large sections of ECG data.
  • Detailed View to observe a zoomed-in section of ECG data with features for annotation. 
  • Add, Edit, and delete beat types, events, and artifacts.
  • HR navigator to observe HR data.
  • Comments or narrative.

Title: Raw ECG Viewer
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall provide a raw ECG viewer to display all available ECG leads individually without analysis for reference during the ECG Technicianโs review
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall provide a raw ECG viewer to display all available ECG leads individually without analysis for reference during the ECG Technician’s review.

Title: ECG Report Preview
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall prompt a preview of the ECG report and allow editing of the report before the final report submission
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall prompt a preview of the ECG report and allow editing of the report before the final report submission.

Title: Mandatory Strips
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall automatically display mandatory strips in the summary page of the report such as AFib/Flutter, Pause, and VT
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall automatically display mandatory strips in the summary page of the report such as AFib/Flutter, Pause, and VT.

Title: Event Counters
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall automatically display event counters in Report.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall automatically display event counters in Report.

Title: Physician's Portal
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall provide a physician overread portal for reviewing and approving or rejecting and electronically signing final reports submitted by technicians
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall provide a physician overread portal for reviewing and approving or rejecting and electronically signing final reports submitted by technicians.

Title: Role and Privileges
Detail: ZBProโข shall provide the capability to assign the following roles and privileges to user accounts
column5: ZBPro™ shall provide the capability to assign the following roles and privileges to user accounts: The Technician privileges shall allow the user to view and annotate the ECG tracing and events, and generate a report. The Medical Supervisor privileges shall allow the users to review, approve or reject a report. The HCP privileges shall allow the user to upload data and patient diary, and get and review the report. The Admin privileges shall allow the user to add, edit, delete the users of the same group, and reset user passwords.

Title: Diary Log Association
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall associate the uploaded Patient's Diary Log with ECG Record.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall associate the uploaded Patient's Diary Log with ECG Record.

Title: ECG Data Association
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall associate uploaded ECG data with an ECG Record.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall associate uploaded ECG data with an ECG Record.

Title: Compatible ECG Data Formats
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall have the ability to process and analyze the ECG data of the following formats
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall have the ability to process and analyze the ECG data of the following formats: (1) a standard MIT-BIH WFDB / PhysioNet ECG data format that consists of a header file (.hea) and a signal file (.dat); (2) a standard ISHNE data format (.ecg); and (3) a standard Health Level 7 (HL7) aECG format (.xml).

Title: Store and Retrive ECG Data
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall be able to store and retrieve computed and annotated ECG data.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall be able to store and retrieve computed and annotated ECG data.

Title: ECG Report Sections
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall generate an ECG report of the patient's data with the following sections
column5:
ZBPro(TM) shall generate an ECG report of the patient's data with the following sections:
  • Summary Page with overall narrative from ECG technician or Medical Supervisor.
  • Heart Rate Summary
  • Atrial Fibrillation / Flutter Hourly Burden
  • Patient Symptoms
  • SVE Burden
  • VE Hourly Burden
  • HR and Ectopic Beats Table
  • Heart Rate Variability
  • Strip Index

Title: User Account Information
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall create, edit and maintain user accounts identifiable by a valid email address and include the following information
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall create, edit and maintain user accounts identifiable by a valid email address and include the following information: date registered, user name, user role, status (active, inactive, suspended), first, middle and last names, email, phone number, and address.

Title: Create and Edit Profiles and Records
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall allow users to create or edit Patient Profiles and patients' Record Profiles
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall allow users to create or edit Patient Profiles and patients' Record Profiles.

Title: Record Status
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall present the Record Status for each record.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall present the Record Status for each record.

Title: Search and Filter Tools
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall provide searching and filter tools to help the user locate a patient's profile and/or record
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall provide searching and filter tools to help the user locate a patient's profile and/or record.

Title: Age Restrictions
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall reject patient profiles and ECG records for patients under 22 years of age
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall reject patient profiles and ECG records for patients under 22 years of age.

Title: Pacemaker Restrictions
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall reject patient profiles and ECG records when a pacemaker is present
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall reject patient profiles and ECG records when a pacemaker is present.

Title: Data Validation
Detail: Data validation shall be implemented including formatted date and time fields, required fields, checkboxes, and confirmation messages, and the system shall raise errors and provide error messages upon error
column5: Data validation shall be implemented including formatted date and time fields, required fields, checkboxes, and confirmation messages, and the system shall raise errors and provide error messages upon error. This includes input in the wrong file format and missing fields on the input file.

Title: Service Unavailable Notifications
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall notify users that services failed or are unavailable.
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall notify users that services failed or are unavailable.

Title: Notifications
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall provide a non-intrusive notification banner to announce new features, product updates, and other important information
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall provide a non-intrusive notification banner to announce new features, product updates, and other important information.

Title: ECG Data API
Detail: ZBPro(TM) API shall accept ECG data.
column5: ZBPro(TM) API shall accept ECG data.

Title: ECG Report API
Detail: ZBPro(TM) API shall return an ECG report in JSON format.
column5: ZBPro(TM) API shall return an ECG report in JSON format.

Title: Authentication API
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall provide an interface for the third-party front-end to authenticate
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall provide an interface for the third-party front-end to authenticate.

Title: Logout API
Detail: ZBPro(TM) API shall terminate the session and invalidate the token upon logout.
column5: ZBPro(TM) API shall terminate the session and invalidate the token upon logout.

Title: Patient Profile API
Detail: ZBPro API shall provide a mechanism to create a Patient Profile.
column5: ZBPro API shall provide a mechanism to create a Patient Profile.

Title: Record API
Detail: ZBPro API shall provide a mechanism to create a Record.
column5: ZBPro API shall provide a mechanism to create a Record.

Title: Record List API
Detail: ZBPro API shall return a Record List
column5: ZBPro API shall return a Record List

Title: Patient List API
Detail: ZBPro API shall return a Patient List
column5: ZBPro API shall return a Patient List

Title: Sole Reliance Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall include a warning stating to not rely on report as the sole means for diagnosis and/or treatment decision
column5: Labeling shall include a warning stating to not rely on report as the sole means for diagnosis and/or treatment decision.

Title: Data Entry Error Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall include a warning to the user that data entry errors can lead to misdiagnosis or incorrect treatment
column5: Labeling shall include a warning to the user that data entry errors can lead to misdiagnosis or incorrect treatment.

Title: ECG Data Verification Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall include a warning to the user that not verifying the ECG data matches with the correct patient can lead to misdiagnosis or incorrect treatment
column5: Labeling shall include a warning to the user that not verifying the ECG data matches with the correct patient can lead to misdiagnosis or incorrect treatment.

Title: Logging out Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall warn the user that not logging out after use may result in sensitive data being exposed to unauthorized personnel
column5: Labeling shall warn the user that not logging out after use may result in sensitive data being exposed to unauthorized personnel.

Title: Signal Quality Labeling
Detail: The user manual shall include a caution statement regarding the quality of the signal (SNR <= 6db), and that the performance might be reduced on lower quality (with artifacts) or inverted ECG data
column5: The user manual shall include a caution statement regarding the quality of the signal (SNR <= 6db), and that the performance might be reduced on lower quality (with artifacts) or inverted ECG data.

Title: Broswer Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall include a caution statement to the user that web browsers other than Google Chrome can lead to features not compatible or available
column5: Labeling shall include a caution statement to the user that web browsers other than Google Chrome can lead to features not compatible or available.

Title: Patient Trigger Event Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall include a caution to the user to focus more on areas where Patient Trigger Events occurred
column5: Labeling shall include a caution to the user to focus more on areas where Patient Trigger Events occurred.

Title: Intended Patients Labeling
Detail: The user manual shall include a precautionary statement that the device is only intended for use on adult patients (over the age of 22) not wearing a pacemaker
column5: The user manual shall include a precautionary statement that the device is only intended for use on adult patients (over the age of 22) not wearing a pacemaker.

Title: Intended Users Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall include a precautionary statement that users must be clinical professionals with knowledge of ECG analysis, be trained in the use of the device, and must read the IFU before use
column5: Labeling shall include a precautionary statement that users must be clinical professionals with knowledge of ECG analysis, be trained in the use of the device, and must read the IFU before use. Inadequate knowledge or training could result in an increased risk of harm to patients.

Title: System Specification Labeling
Detail: Labeling shall explain the required system specifications to be compatible with ZBPro
column5: Labeling shall explain the required system specifications to be compatible with ZBPro.

Title: Performance Accuracy Labeling
Detail: The user manual shall disclose the complete detection scope and performance accuracy of ZBPro
column5: The user manual shall disclose the complete detection scope and performance accuracy of ZBPro.

Title: Resourse Labeling
Detail: ZBPro(TM) shall provide written instructions for use, user training, and help or tip function for user reference
column5: ZBPro(TM) shall provide written instructions for use, user training, and help or tip function for user reference.

Title: RxOnly Labeling
Detail: ZBProโข primary label and User / Developer manuals shall bear the RxOnly statement
column5: ZBPro™ primary label and User / Developer manuals shall bear the RxOnly statement.

Title: API Labeling
Detail: ZBPro shall provide sufficient instructions to create a valid API call, and a list of compatible data, and explain that API calls must be submitted from whitelisted networks and tokens
column5: ZBPro shall provide sufficient instructions to create a valid API call, and a list of compatible data, and explain that API calls must be submitted from whitelisted networks and tokens.

Title: Prevent use of Public Networks
Detail: Uploaded files using ZBPro Web GUI or API shall not be transmitted over the public internet
column5: Uploaded files using ZBPro Web GUI or API shall not be transmitted over the public internet. (CTA-CC21)

Title: Password Expiration
Detail: ZBPro Web user passwords shall expire after 180 days. (CTA-CC22)
column5: ZBPro Web user passwords shall expire after 180 days. (CTA-CC22)

Title: Account Locked Out
Detail: ZBPro Web users shall be locked out after 3 failed login attempts. (CTA-CC23)
column5: ZBPro Web users shall be locked out after 3 failed login attempts. (CTA-CC23)

Title: Unreadable Password
Detail: ZBPro Web ensures that the password shall be unreadable to the User. (CTA-CC24)
column5: ZBPro Web ensures that the password shall be unreadable to the User. (CTA-CC24)

Title: Frontend Password Requirements
Detail: Passwords shall have a minimum of 8 characters, and contain at least one number, at least one upper case letter, at least one lower case letter, and at least one special character
column5: Passwords shall have a minimum of 8 characters, and contain at least one number, at least one upper case letter, at least one lower case letter, and at least one special character. (CTA-CC25, CTA-CC49)

Title: PHI/PII Cache Prevention
Detail: The ZBPro Web GUI shall never cache any PHI/PII on the User's Laptop/PC
column5: The ZBPro Web GUI shall never cache any PHI/PII on the User's Laptop/PC. (CTA-CC26)

Title: Two-Factor Authentication in GUI
Detail: Two-factor authentication shall be implemented on the ZBPro Web GUI to ensure that only authorized users access the system
column5: Two-factor authentication shall be implemented on the ZBPro Web GUI to ensure that only authorized users access the system. (CTA-CC27)

Title: Auto-Logout
